Data Analysis and Statistics Applications in Insurance

Chia Ying Lee
13 Nov 2018

Risk Analysis in (P&C) Insurance

  • Given risk factors, get loss (i.e., risk) predictions.

    • Used in pricing policies
    • When a catastrophe hits, insurers need to assess building damage and portfolio loss.

  • Complex physical models of catastrophes are extensive to build.
    Some companies specialize in risk analysis of catastrophes (AIR, RMS, etc.)

Risk Aggregation

  • Catastrophe hits \( \longrightarrow \) loss distribution reflects model uncertainty.
  • Aggregation of risks: \( L_{portfolio} = L_1 + \dots + L_N \)

Risk Aggregation

  • Monte Carlo simulation

    • Slow convergence, curse of dimensionality
    • Use quasi-Monte Carlo for non-random computations

  • Convolutions

    • \( f_{portfolio} = f_1 \ast \dots \ast f_N \)
    • Brute-force convolution in high dimension is intractable
    • Can use approximations, e.g., regridding the domain

Incorporating Spatial Correlations

  • Risks \( (L_1, \dots, L_N) \) are correlated in space
  • Know marginals \( F_1, \dots, F_n \)
  • Need to impose correlation for joint distribution
  • Copula model: “links” together marginals to yield a joint distribution
    \[ F(x_1, \dots, x_n) = C(F_1(x_1), \dots, F_n(x_n)) \]
    (Sklar's Theorem)
    • Copula \( C \) is a multivariate uniform CDF.

Copula Models

  • Gaussian copula \[ \Phi_{\Sigma} (z_1, \dots, z_n) = C_{\Sigma} (\Phi(z_1), \dots, \Phi(z_n)) \]
    • Links together Gaussian marginals to yield multivariate Gaussian with covariance matrix \( \Sigma \).

Copula Models

  • t-copula (has tail dependence)

  • Comonotonic copula: \( C(u_1, \dots, u_n) = \min(u_1, \dots, u_n) \)

    • Perfect dependence: from a uniform draw \( U \),
      \[ X_1 = F_1^{-1} (U), \dots, X_n = F_n^{-1} (U) \]
    • RHS is the Frechet-Hoeffding upper bound

Copula Sampling

  • Draw a copula sample \( (U_1, \dots, U_n) \)

    • Apply the inverse probability transform
      \[ X_1 = F_1^{-1} (U_1), \dots, X_n = F_n^{-1} (U_n) \]

  • Iman-Conover reordering

    • Draw \( K \) copula samples \( U_1^{k}, \dots, U_n^{k} \).
    • Draw \( K \) independent marginals \( X_1^{k}, \dots, X_n^{k} \).
    • Reorder the marginal samples to have the same rank ordering as the copula samples

Portfolio Loss Analysis

  • Stochastic catalog: large collection of simulated (catastrophic) events
  • Purpose: estimate Average Annual Loss of a portfolio
  • Event Clustering: Cluster together similar events –> Eliminate computations of events that cause similar losses

Event Clustering via Spatial Footprint


Tornado swaths of two events.

  • Kernel mapping from 5 ellipse parameters into high (infinite) dimensional space
  • Kernel inner product \( \langle E_1, E_2\rangle = \) non-overlap area.
  • Apply kernel k-means
